# Project-wide ShellCheck configuration for vpssec.
#
# Every disable below has a specific justification recorded here. Before
# adding a new rule to the list, prefer a per-site `# shellcheck disable=SCxxxx`
# directive with a one-line comment — global disables only for rules that
# fire many times across the project or represent structural choices.
#
# Tested against ShellCheck 0.11.0 (pinned in .github/workflows/shellcheck.yml).

# Resolve `source` targets when they are statically analyzable.
external-sources=true

disable=SC1091,SC2005,SC2016,SC2034,SC2053,SC2064,SC2076,SC2128,SC2129,SC2155,SC2178,SC2183,SC2235,SC2001,SC2010,SC2012

# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Justifications
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# SC1091 — "source target not found". Modules are sourced via dynamic paths
#          such as "${VPSSEC_CORE}/common.sh"; shellcheck cannot resolve the
#          interpolation at analysis time.
#
# SC2005 — "useless echo $(...)". Cosmetic; rewriting 5 call sites offers no
#          functional gain.
#
# SC2016 — "expressions in single quotes won't expand". Used intentionally when
#          the project generates systemd units / nginx configs / audit rules
#          where expansion must happen at runtime, not at template-build time.
#
# SC2034 — "unused variable". Globals like RED, GREEN, SYM_OK, SEV_HIGH are
#          defined in core/common.sh and consumed by sourced modules;
#          shellcheck's per-file view cannot see that cross-file usage.
#
# SC2053 — "quote right-hand side of == to prevent glob matching". Used
#          deliberately in filesystem.sh whitelist matching where glob
#          semantics are the goal (see comment at the call site).
#
# SC2064 — "use single quotes for trap to defer expansion". The one site
#          (core/engine.sh) traps a path from mktemp that will not change
#          between trap-set and trap-fire, so both forms are equivalent.
#
# SC2076 — "remove quotes from regex RHS of =~". The one site (ufw.sh) uses
#          a space-padded literal-substring match pattern; dropping quotes
#          would change the semantics to regex, which is not what the author
#          wants.
#
# SC2128 — "expanding array without index". Pairs with SC2178 below — both
#          are false positives caused by shellcheck conflating an array
#          inside a helper function with a same-named string local in the
#          caller's scope.
#
# SC2129 — "combine multiple >> redirects". Cosmetic.
#
# SC2155 — "declare and assign separately". Fires 670+ times across the
#          project where `local foo=$(cmd)` is the established idiom.
#          Changing every site would dwarf this PR and carries real
#          regression risk; the underlying concern (masked return codes)
#          is already handled where it matters by `set -e` + explicit
#          `|| true` / fallback patterns.
#
# SC2178 — see SC2128.
#
# SC2183 — "printf has N variables but M arguments". False positive on
#          printf '%*s' where the `*` is a width-from-argument specifier,
#          not a second variable.
#
# SC2235 — "use { ..; } instead of (..) subshell". The one site
#          (webapp.sh _webapp_apache_installed) uses parentheses for
#          short-circuit grouping; subshell cost here is immaterial.
#
# SC2001 — "use ${var//pat/rep} instead of sed". Cosmetic.
#
# SC2010 — "don't use ls | grep". The one site reads /proc/<pid>/fd,
#          where filenames are kernel-generated integers and the output
#          format is fixed; the generic concern about unusual filenames
#          does not apply.
#
# SC2012 — "use find instead of ls". The two sites list timestamp-formatted
#          backup dirs (YYYYMMDD_HHMMSS) and /var/spool/cron/crontabs, both
#          of which hold well-formed names.
